e-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><em>Denver Rayburn</em></p><blockquote sty=
le=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427;margin: 20px 0;padding: 0;"><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);margin-left: 20px;line-height: =
26px;font-size: 16px;"><em><span>Today, we stand at another such moment. In=
telligence, automation, and cheap abundant energy are converging to rewrite=
 the economics of production. Beyond industrial or trade policy, something =
more profound is changing: the underlying cost physics of manufacturing (co=
ined with inspiration from </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/=
5e9aacbd-deff-4d27-873e-04cc88784a48?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);text-d=
ecoration: underline;">Coogan&#8217;s Law</a><span>.) And unlike previous t=
echnological revolutions, this transformation may be permanent &#8211; crea=
ting a lasting shift that uniquely favors American manufacturing.</span></e=
m></p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line=
-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">America&#8217;s role in the world has chang=
ed many times in its history.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(=
54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Hell, America&#8217;s role in=
 the world has changed many times over the last 6 weeks.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Mo=
re and more folks believe that America once again has to, and can, take on =
its role of the manufacturing powerhouse it once was. Denver Rayburn, in th=
is excellent primer, lays out his thinking on how America may be favorably =
positioned to take on that role once again.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Rayburn argues =
that the convergence of AI, automation, and cheap energy is permanently res=
haping manufacturing economics and eliminating the labor cost arbitrage tha=
t drove manufacturing out of the U.S. in the first place. In a world where =
labor cost is no longer the primary input cost, a country that has abundant=
 and cheap energy, the capital markets to finance an automation rollout, an=
d is a leader in artificial intelligence finds itself in a very strong posi=
tion. Thankfully, the U.S. checks all of those boxes.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">It&#8=
217;s kind of scary to think how much of U.S. foreign and domestic policy r=
eally hinges on a) whether or not this transition is actually underway and =
b) how well positioned the U.S. is in this transition. Let&#8217;s hope Ray=
burn is right and that both the government and private sector take advantag=
e of this unique opportunity in history to rebuild America as a manufacturi=
ng hub.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height:=
